Hi.

This is a Savage Cub Single Shot .22lr Youth Rifle with very nice real wood and a 16" barrel.  Note that this is not the smaller, more cheaply made Savage Rascal, but the now-discontinued Cub, which was based on their full-sized rimfire line.  The iron sights have been removed. title: For Sale:  Kimber of Oregon Model 82G Government .22 target rifle
postcontent:
The Kimber of Oregon 82G is a single-shot, 1-in-16 twist, Heavy 25” barrel bolt action target rifle. The butt stock is adjustable for length of pull and all spacers are included. Sling swivel is adjustable to the shooter. Sights are at 1/5 MOA per click. Trigger is factory set for 3.5 lbs but is fully adjustable. Incredibly precise click adjust rear and front iron sights are mounted on 18mm rails; I dropped a scope on it (not included).  Includes target sights with 8 drop-in reticles, original certificate of authenticity from CMP, manual, box.

US Gov't ordered 20,000 of these precision target rifles for training back in the 80s. Many sat in a warehouse for 25+ years before they were sold through the Civilian Marksmanship Program, where I bought mine 18 months ago. 

The pictures in ad are not mine, I grabbed them from the internet, but they show both the included target iron sights and what it would look like if you scope it.

The finish and stock are in excellent condition, it looks brand new. I took it out of the original box, gave it a complete disassembly, cleaned it thoroughly and fired it at the Redmond Gun Club range where it was much admired, but I discovered I am not a steady enough shooter at my age for bench shooting. It has less than 500 rounds through it. 

If you are looking to get into smallbore bench shooting, this is simply the least expensive way to get in without dumping 1400 bucks into the lower-end anschutz rifles. Absolutely no rust, excellent condition, very accurate.  Face-to-face in Bend/Redmond area, no shipping, Oregon ID and bill of sale required.  

I also have several bricks (500 rounds) of Golden Eagle Eley Prime target ammo that I will offer to the purchaser for $50 each.  The 82G shoots well with this round.

title: For Sale:   3 Piece Combo-Warne 30mm RAMP Mount, 45 Degree Side Mount and 1inch AR Skel Mount.
postcontent:
This is a 3 piece combo. R.A.M.P. 1Inch SKEL Mount and the 45 degree mount.
The all new WARNE Rapid Acquisition Multi-Sight Platform, or RAMP, is a cantilever style scope mounting platform that allows proper scope installation on the popular AR-15 rifle. By design, the AR platform was intended for fixed iron sights and did not offer an acceptable mounting surface for optics. As the weapon system evolved from the military designate M16A1 to the M16A3 and M4, Picatinny mounting systems became standard equipment, however, the rail system found on the A3 and M4 weapon systems still did not allow a variable power optic to be mounted far enough forward with conventional scope mounts.

The new Warne RAMP modular mounting system positions the front ring forward of the upper receiver by 1 3/4” allowing the optics to be mounted farther forward allowing the shooter to position their head in the proper position whether upright or prone and not sacrifice their shooting position due to improper optic positioning.

The new Warne RAMP also offers unique 45 degree mounting rails on one or both sides of the optic. As you know, variable power optics are great for distance but not CQB scenarios. Additionally, CQB sights are great for close quarters and entry scenarios but not for distance shots or target ID. So which one do you choose? Why not have both? The R.A.M.P provides exactly that. The primary sight can be as small as a 1-4 or as large as an 8.5-25 or larger variable power optic. With a mini red dot on one or both sides of the ocular, a shooter can transition from scope to dot or dot to scope in less than a second by rotating the weapon 45 degrees left or right. While the technique is not new, the position of the red dot is. By placing the sight under the ocular of the scope, we have provided a wider field of view thru the mini red dot and make acquiring the dot in the sight faster than you can imagine. And once again, you won’t have to sacrifice your shooting position when transitioning from sight to sight.

FEATURES:
•6000 Series Aluminum
•#8 Torx style fasteners with steel threaded inserts
•Cantilever design for proper eye relief
•Dual 45 degree mounting rails (with the option to remove one or both) for quick transition between scope and red dot
•1/2″ tactical nut attachment, 65 in/lb of torque is recommended

The 1inch SKEL Mount is a one piece mount.
 45 Degree Mount. Machined 6061 aluminum with a durable anodized matte black. For use with a Flat Top AR-15 and other tactical firearms. Provides a 45° accessory mounting platform that attaches to a Picatinny rail for use of flashlights, lasers, slings or open sights without obstructing your sight line. Designed to co-witness with the side rails of the R.A.M.P. Mount to allow the use of popup or fixed type combat or open sights.

title: For Sale:  SVT 40 Naval Stock extremely well kept
postcontent:
For sale is an SVT 40. It has VERY strong rifling and a bore like a mirror. The gas system looks factory new, which is rare for 72 year old rifle that shot corrosive ammo during the war. The stock is a Naval/marine stock as it has a sling loop integrated into the buttstock much like a Mosin. The fact that it is a naval rifle may account for how good a shape the internals are. Naval infantry and the marines did fight the Germans on land, however it was to a much lesser extent than the Red Army itself. The serial number stamped into the stock matches that of the rifle. The stock is a deep Russian red, as it was during the war. The wood does show signs of its age with various scratches attained over time, but such is to be expected of a surplus rifle. There are NO cracks what so ever. The metal pieces are in great shape with its finish still intact with hardly any wear. The bolt is a plum color due to the cleaning solvents the Russians used, but this is common and does not affect the function. The muzzle brake is that of the Early period, as it has several line ports rather than two big ports like that on the AVT40. 

You will never find an SVT in this shape that isn't in a museum. In fact, you won't see any new ones imported unless you're in Canada, as Clinton put an end to that in the 90s. The rifle does have some electric penciling of serial numbers in spots as the Russians tended to force match these after the war. If it was not, I would be asking much more. The one that isn't is the one I'm keeping! 


You can have a piece of history, and the honor to say you own a rifle that is extremely rare, and sought after.

As far as price goes, if I get what I ask, I will be willing to travel, any lower and I'm not leaving Columbus.  It is more than a fair price, Gunbroker and other SVTs on Armslist will show you that. 

One mag included, maybe some ammo if the deal is right.  Must be legally able to own this, will ask for ID. No trades at this time, please. Do your research before offering me, "500 BUCKS MEET TODAY"
